    "body": "![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)

There's an issue with the error handling logic in this block. The `catch` block is currently unreachable, and failed requests do not provide any feedback to the user in the UI.

The root cause is that the `fetchData` helper function catches all exceptions, shows a generic `alert()`, and returns `null` instead of re-throwing the error. Consequently, a failure in `fetchData` results in `result` being `null`, which executes the `else` block (lines 680-682). This block only logs to the console, leaving the user with a disabled "Saving..." button and no indication of what went wrong.

To fix this and make your new inline error display work as intended, two changes are needed:

1.  **Modify `fetchData` to re-throw errors:** The `catch` block in `fetchData` (lines 150-154) should be changed to not show an `alert` and to re-throw the error, allowing the caller to handle it.

    ```javascript
    // In fetchData()
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
        throw error; // Re-throw the error instead of returning null
    }
    ```

2.  **Remove the `else` block in this function:** With `fetchData` throwing errors, the `else` block here becomes unnecessary and should be removed. The `catch` block will then correctly handle all error scenarios.

After these changes, a failed request will be caught by this `catch` block, and the user will see the intended error message in the modal.",
